title Personal Computing in the Age of Conversational AI (2026)
style wardley

// ------------------------------------------------------------
// Anchor: the developer (and end-user of personal computing),
// whose need is to build and run software.
// ------------------------------------------------------------
anchor Developer (End User) [0.98, 0.45]
anchor Need: Build & Ship Software [0.94, 0.50]

// ------------------------------------------------------------
// User-facing surfaces: applications and devices
// (the visible "tip of the iceberg")
// ------------------------------------------------------------
component Applications [0.88, 0.72]
component Devices (Laptop / Desktop / Mobile) [0.86, 0.90]

// ------------------------------------------------------------
// IDE layer — split into human-centric and conversational modes
// Human-centric IDEs are mature products; conversational
// (AI+human) IDEs are still emerging from custom-built.
// ------------------------------------------------------------
component IDE (Human-centric) [0.78, 0.70]
component IDE (Conversational AI+Human) [0.76, 0.28]

// ------------------------------------------------------------
// Supporting reusable building blocks and legacy approaches.
// Libraries/services are product-stage; legacy approaches are
// commodity but with strong inertia.
// ------------------------------------------------------------
component Component Libraries & Services [0.68, 0.68]
component Legacy Approaches (Waterfall / Scripted) [0.66, 0.80]

// ------------------------------------------------------------
// Runtime layer
// Serverless is productised and heading to commodity.
// LAMP/.Net is a commodity runtime stack with inertia.
// LLM inference runtime sits early — genesis/custom.
// FinOps (cost governance for cloud & LLMs) is custom→product.
// ------------------------------------------------------------
component Runtime: Serverless (FaaS) [0.58, 0.66]
component Runtime: LAMP / .Net [0.56, 0.85]
component Large Language Models (LLMs) [0.60, 0.22]
component FinOps (Cloud / LLM Cost Governance) [0.62, 0.38]

// ------------------------------------------------------------
// Operating systems & orchestration
// OSes are commodity; Kubernetes-class orchestration is
// product heading to commodity.
// ------------------------------------------------------------
component Operating Systems [0.46, 0.88]
component Orchestration Tools (Kubernetes etc.) [0.48, 0.70]

// ------------------------------------------------------------
// Containers & DevOps
// Containers are commodity; DevOps practices are product.
// Legacy architecture (monoliths, pet servers) is commodity
// with heavy inertia.
// ------------------------------------------------------------
component Containers [0.38, 0.86]
component DevOps (CI/CD, IaC, SRE) [0.40, 0.68]
component Legacy Architecture (Monoliths / Pet Servers) [0.36, 0.78]

// ------------------------------------------------------------
// Compute — the utility foundation
// Cloud compute is near-pure utility; on-prem servers are
// commodity but visibly less far right than the hyperscalers.
// ------------------------------------------------------------
component Compute: Servers (On-Prem) [0.18, 0.78]
component Compute: Cloud (IaaS / Hyperscaler) [0.12, 0.94]

// ------------------------------------------------------------
// Dependencies (a -> b means a depends on b)
// ------------------------------------------------------------

// Developer + their need
Developer (End User)->Need: Build & Ship Software
Need: Build & Ship Software->Applications
Need: Build & Ship Software->Devices (Laptop / Desktop / Mobile)
Need: Build & Ship Software->IDE (Human-centric)
Need: Build & Ship Software->IDE (Conversational AI+Human)

// Applications depend on the toolchain & runtime
Applications->IDE (Human-centric)
Applications->IDE (Conversational AI+Human)
Applications->Component Libraries & Services
Applications->Runtime: Serverless (FaaS)
Applications->Runtime: LAMP / .Net
Applications->Devices (Laptop / Desktop / Mobile)

// Devices run on an OS
Devices (Laptop / Desktop / Mobile)->Operating Systems

// IDE (human-centric) depends on OS, libs, legacy approaches
IDE (Human-centric)->Operating Systems
IDE (Human-centric)->Component Libraries & Services
IDE (Human-centric)->Legacy Approaches (Waterfall / Scripted)

// IDE (conversational) depends on LLMs, libs, OS, FinOps
IDE (Conversational AI+Human)->Large Language Models (LLMs)
IDE (Conversational AI+Human)->Component Libraries & Services
IDE (Conversational AI+Human)->Operating Systems
IDE (Conversational AI+Human)->FinOps (Cloud / LLM Cost Governance)

// Libraries / legacy approaches depend on runtime
Component Libraries & Services->Runtime: Serverless (FaaS)
Component Libraries & Services->Runtime: LAMP / .Net
Legacy Approaches (Waterfall / Scripted)->Runtime: LAMP / .Net
Legacy Approaches (Waterfall / Scripted)->Legacy Architecture (Monoliths / Pet Servers)

// Runtime depends on orchestration / OS / containers
Runtime: Serverless (FaaS)->Orchestration Tools (Kubernetes etc.)
Runtime: Serverless (FaaS)->Containers
Runtime: LAMP / .Net->Operating Systems
Runtime: LAMP / .Net->Legacy Architecture (Monoliths / Pet Servers)

// LLM runtime depends on cloud compute + FinOps
Large Language Models (LLMs)->Compute: Cloud (IaaS / Hyperscaler)
Large Language Models (LLMs)->FinOps (Cloud / LLM Cost Governance)
Large Language Models (LLMs)->Containers

// FinOps depends on cloud
FinOps (Cloud / LLM Cost Governance)->Compute: Cloud (IaaS / Hyperscaler)

// Orchestration / containers / OS stack
Orchestration Tools (Kubernetes etc.)->Containers
Orchestration Tools (Kubernetes etc.)->Operating Systems
Containers->Operating Systems
Operating Systems->Compute: Servers (On-Prem)
Operating Systems->Compute: Cloud (IaaS / Hyperscaler)

// DevOps glues orchestration + runtime + legacy
DevOps (CI/CD, IaC, SRE)->Containers
DevOps (CI/CD, IaC, SRE)->Orchestration Tools (Kubernetes etc.)
DevOps (CI/CD, IaC, SRE)->Runtime: Serverless (FaaS)
DevOps (CI/CD, IaC, SRE)->Legacy Architecture (Monoliths / Pet Servers)

// Legacy architecture runs on on-prem or cloud
Legacy Architecture (Monoliths / Pet Servers)->Compute: Servers (On-Prem)
Legacy Architecture (Monoliths / Pet Servers)->Compute: Cloud (IaaS / Hyperscaler)

// ------------------------------------------------------------
// Movement (→ evolving, >> accelerating, x inertia)
// ------------------------------------------------------------
evolve IDE (Conversational AI+Human) 0.62 // → product over ~2-3 yrs
evolve Large Language Models (LLMs) 0.55   // → product-stage via hosted APIs
evolve FinOps (Cloud / LLM Cost Governance) 0.60
evolve Runtime: Serverless (FaaS) 0.82     // → commodity
evolve Orchestration Tools (Kubernetes etc.) 0.86
evolve Component Libraries & Services 0.80
evolve Applications 0.82
evolve Compute: Servers (On-Prem) 0.90     // being absorbed into cloud

// Inertia markers (components stuck right but with resistance)
annotation 1 [0.56, 0.85] Inertia: LAMP/.Net still entrenched in enterprise
annotation 2 [0.36, 0.78] Inertia: legacy monoliths / pet servers
annotation 3 [0.66, 0.80] Inertia: waterfall / scripted legacy approaches

annotations [0.02, 0.92]

// ------------------------------------------------------------
// Notes
// - ν(a) ≥ ν(b) holds on every edge above.
// - Cloud/containers are the commoditised utility floor (right).
// - LLMs and conversational IDEs are the genesis/custom frontier
//   that is reshaping what "personal computing" means for
//   developers building software in 2026.
// ------------------------------------------------------------
